{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's *Saqaliya*, the most charged moment arrives at the opening, where the poet exhorts tears over Sicily as \"the grave of Hejazi civilization,\" soon evoking the past conquering Muslims whose \"resurrecting call\" revived a dead world.[^1][^2] Yet the poet claims intimate kinship with this lost Muslim glory—he is \"pain incarnate,\" \"the dust of that caravan\" destined for Sicily—and vows to carry its grief \"as a gift to Hindustan\" to make others weep, preserving the pain as fuel for communal revival.[^3] This speaker is *permitted* to imagine restoration: his people achieved it once before, and his verse awakens that memory toward future Islamic renewal.\n\nIn the Old English *The Ruin* (ch. 16 of *Old English Elegies*), the charged moment fuses present desolation with recalled past in the opening: the \"wondrous... wall-stone, by Wyrd broken,\" \"the work of giants crumbles,\" its builders gripped eternally by earth after \"a hundred generations,\" amid memories of bright halls, baths, and mead-drinking warriors.[^4][^5] The speaker marvels at alien *enta geweorc* (\"giants' work,\" i.e., Roman masonry) from before living memory but remains a mere witness to *wyrd*'s finality—no kinship, no claim staked, no resurrection voiced or ventured. This speaker is *not* permitted to imagine restoration: fatalistic contemplation bars any human counter to cosmic decay.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 (*Saqaliya*), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-08760e).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 (*Saqaliya*), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-ab88c0).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 (*Saqaliya*), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-665fb2).\n\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 16 (*The Ruin*), [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-d0d2bd).\n\n[^5]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 16 (*The Ruin*), [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-ba51da).",
